    "summary": "The microprocessor, a complete central processing unit fabricated on a single integrated circuit chip, was invented in 1971 when Intel released the 4004, designed by engineers Federico Faggin, Ted Hoff, and Stanley Mazor. This development consolidated what had previously required rooms full of equipment into a component smaller than a fingernail. The 4004 was followed by increasingly powerful designs — the 8008, 8080, and eventually the 8086 family — that became the basis for the personal computer industry.\n\nThe microprocessor's significance lay in making computing economically accessible. Before the microprocessor, computers were expensive capital equipment owned by corporations and governments. After it, computing power became a commodity that could be embedded in consumer products, industrial equipment, and communications systems. The microprocessor underpinned the [[event:2743|personal computer revolution]] of the late 1970s and 1980s and, by extension, the broader digital transformation of the global economy by century's end.",
